This is the story's MODULATION: most beats are quiet and load-bearing; only a few
are charged. A story where every beat runs hot is exhausting to read — a plain
baseline is what makes the peaks land.

Assign each beat exactly one SCENE TYPE (Swain's beat rhythm):

- scene — ACTIVE CONFLICT. A character pursues a goal against an obstacle and the
  situation turns. This is where the prose may rise and run longer. A beat that
  COMMITS or COMPLICATES a dilemma is almost always a scene; so is any
  confrontation, decision, discovery that forces action, or reversal.
- sequel — REACTIVE PROCESSING. The decompression between scenes: a character
  absorbs what just happened, feels it, weighs it, and decides what to do next.
  Plain, shorter prose. A quiet ADVANCES or REVEALS beat is usually a sequel.
- micro_beat — PURE TRANSITION. A brief connective moment that carries the reader
  from one place or time to the next. The shortest, lowest-key prose.

Anchors for structural beats that carry no dilemma impact:
- a SETUP beat orients the reader in the world before any dilemma opens -> sequel
  by default (plain, establishing), unless it stages an active moment of its own,
  then scene.
- an EPILOGUE beat winds the story down -> sequel.

Choosing the type sets the writer's word band and intensity, so choose for
MODULATION across the whole story: a plain baseline of sequels and micro-beats
with scenes reserved for the charged turns. Do NOT label everything a scene — that
is the exact failure this pass exists to prevent.

Also assign each beat one NARRATION SCOPE:

- limited — narrated inside the sequence's viewpoint. Almost every beat is
  limited: the reader is with the head, so no other character's private thoughts
  are stated. (This does NOT forbid stating a world fact the narrator could
  plausibly know or observe; scope is about whose knowledge the narration is
  bound to, not how wide the camera pulls back.)
- wide — a detached CODA, narrated from BEYOND any single character's perception.
  Use this ONLY for a beat whose content no viewpoint character could deliver
  at all: a world aftermath once the story's dilemmas have resolved, or a
  character's reputation or fate AFTER they have exited the story. An EPILOGUE
  beat is wide by default. When in doubt, choose limited — defaulting to wide
  licenses the writer to leave the viewpoint.

THE SEQUENCES. The engine has computed the story's sequences — the maximal
stretches with no choice inside them. The reader turns no page mid-sequence
except where YOU put one, and a head-switch is always a page-turn; so the
unit of viewpoint is the sequence, not the beat. For each sequence assign ONE
head: the character whose perception, stakes, and inner reaction the stretch
lives in — who uncovers, notices, suspects, decides, fears across it — not
merely someone present. A rotating scheme rotates BETWEEN sequences, where
page-turns already exist; a single-head scheme names the same head on every
sequence (correct, not a failure to vary).

Split a sequence ONLY where its dramatic center genuinely moves mid-stretch:
name the beat after which the head changes and state the shift in one line
("the discovery is hers, the aftermath is his") — an unearned split is a
page-turn the reader pays for nothing. A head of "" makes the rest of the
segment a WIDE CUTAWAY: every beat in it must be marked wide, and the cutaway
should be as rare as wide itself. When no roster head spans a sequence (the
listing says so), split it where the center shifts or justify a cutaway.

